{{BC-year-stub}}

[[File:Anoshazad in the Shahnameh.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Anoshazad in the [[Shahnameh]].]] '''Anoshazad''', known in the [[Shahnameh]] as '''Noshzad''' (meaning "son of the immortal"), was a [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]] prince who was the leader of a revolt in southern [[Iran]] in ca. 550. He was the oldest son of king [[Khosrow I]] (r. 531-579), while his mother was a [[Christianity|Christian]] and the daughter of the judge (''[[dadwar]]'') of [[Ray, Iran|Ray]].
== Biography == === Etymology === ''Anōshāzād'' is a [[Middle Persian]] name, while ''Nōshzād'' ({{lang|fa|نوشزاد}}) is the [[New Persian]] form. The [[Greek language|Greek]] form of the name is ''Anasozados''. Whether it is really a proper name, or rather an epithet, is unclear.
===Imprisonment=== [[File:Southwestern part of the Sasanian Empire.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Map of the southwestern part of the [[Sasanian Empire]].]] According to several sources, Anoshazad was sometime before his revolt imprisoned in [[Gundeshapur]] by his father. According to [[Abū Ḥanīfa Dīnawarī|Dinavari]] and [[Ferdowsi]], it was because he had converted to [[Christianity]]. However, this is unlikely since neither [[Procopius]] nor [[Ali ibn al-Athir|Ibn al-Athir]] calls him a Christian; according to Procopius, Anoshazad was imprisoned for seducing some of his father's wives, while Ibn al-Athir states that he was imprisoned because he was suspected of being a crypto-[[Manichaean]].{{sfn|Khaleghi-Motlagh|1985|pp=99-100}}
=== Revolt === According to Dinavari, while Khosrow I was campaigning in Syria against the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]], he fell ill at [[Homs|Emesa]]—according to [[Theodor Nöldeke|Nöldeke]], however, Khosrow never reached the city and instead returned to his capital, [[Ctesiphon]]. He further states that Anoshazad had spread false rumours of Khosrow having a deadly sickness. Anoshazad thereafter raised an army, which consisted of prisoners and Christians from [[Ahvaz]] and [[Gundeshapur]].{{sfn|Khaleghi-Motlagh|1985|pp=99-100}} However, according to Nöldeke, Fariburz most likely didn't manage to get support from a large number of Christians, which he tried to do so by stating that his mother was a Christian. Nevertheless, he managed to capture Ahvaz and seize its riches.{{sfn|Khaleghi-Motlagh|1985|pp=99-100}}
Burzin, who was Khosrow's vice-regent at Ctesiphon, shortly sent an army under [[Fariburz]] to besiege Gundeshapur, and informed Khosrow of the revolt. Khosrow thereafter ordered him bring Anoshazad back alive if possible, and to kill all the nobles participating in his revolt, but not the ordinary people.{{sfn|Khaleghi-Motlagh|1985|pp=99-100}} The revolt of Anoshazad was eventually suppressed, while he was captured and taken to Ctesiphon, where he was blinded.{{sfn|Khaleghi-Motlagh|1985|pp=99-100}}
