{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}
[[File:Edinburgh District Council election, 1984.svg|thumb|Map showing the results by Council ward.]]
[[File:Red flag.svg|thumb|Following the historic election a red flag was raised above the city chambers, although it was soon taken down.]]
'''Elections for the City of Edinburgh District Council''' took place on Thursday 3 May 1984, alongside [[Scottish District local elections, 1984|elections to the councils]] of Scotland's various other districts.

The election was the first time Labour had ever won a majority on the Edinburgh Council, with the party winning 34 of the City's 62 seats. The Conservatives came second, on 22 seats, whilst the SDP-Liberal Alliance won 4, and the SNP 2. Labour would retain its dominance for the next 23 years, until the [[City of Edinburgh Council election, 2007|2007 election]]. [[Mark Lazarowicz]] and [[Nigel Griffiths]] played prominent roles in the election, and would later both become Edinburgh Members of Parliament for Labour.<ref name="EEV">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=8 April 2014 |title=30 years since Labour took Edinburgh City Council |url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/life-style/30-years-since-labour-took-edinburgh-city-council-1-3368946 |newspaper=Edinburgh Evening News |location= |access-date=8 April 2015 }}</ref> [[Alex Wood (politician)|Alex Wood]] was the leader of the Labour group.

Following the election a [[Red flag (politics)|red flag]] was raised above the [[Edinburgh City Chambers]], but it was taken down after a day.<ref name="EEV"/>

